  "prompt": "What is the proof for triangular law of vectors?",
  "response": "The **Triangular Law of Vectors** is a fundamental concept in vector addition. It states that if two vectors are represented in magnitude and direction by the two sides of a triangle taken in order, then the resultant vector is represented in magnitude and direction by the third side of the triangle taken in the opposite order.\n\n### **Proof of the Triangular Law of Vectors**\n\nLet\u2019s consider two vectors \\(\\mathbf{A}\\) and \\(\\mathbf{B}\\), and we want to find the resultant vector \\(\\mathbf{R} = \\mathbf{A} + \\mathbf{B}\\).\n\n---\n\n### 1. Graphical Representation:\n- Draw vector \\(\\mathbf{A}\\) starting from a point \\(O\\) to a point \\(P\\).\n- From the terminal point \\(P\\) of \\(\\mathbf{A}\\), draw vector \\(\\mathbf{B}\\) to a point \\(Q\\).\n- The vector from the starting point \\(O\\) to the terminal point \\(Q\\) represents the resultant vector \\(\\mathbf{R} = \\mathbf{A} + \\mathbf{B}\\).\n\nThis forms a triangle \\(OPQ\\), where:\n   - \\(OP = \\mathbf{A}\\)\n   - \\(PQ = \\mathbf{B}\\)\n   - \\(OQ = \\mathbf{R} = \\mathbf{A} + \\mathbf{B}\\)\n\n---\n\n### 2. Mathematical Proof:\nUsing the **Cosine Law**, we can derive the magnitude and direction of the resultant vector \\(\\mathbf{R}\\).\n\n#### Magnitude of \\(\\mathbf{R}\\):\nThe magnitude of \\(\\mathbf{R}\\) is given by:\n\\[\n|\\mathbf{R}| = \\sqrt{|\\mathbf{A}|^2 + |\\mathbf{B}|^2 + 2|\\mathbf{A}||\\mathbf{B}|\\cos\\theta}\n\\]\nwhere \\(\\theta\\) is the angle between vectors \\(\\mathbf{A}\\) and \\(\\mathbf{B}\\).\n\n#### Direction of \\(\\mathbf{R}\\):\nThe direction of \\(\\mathbf{R}\\) (angle \\(\\phi\\) with respect to \\(\\mathbf{A}\\)) is given by:\n\\[\n\\phi = \\tan^{-1}\\left(\\frac{|\\mathbf{B}|\\sin\\theta}{|\\mathbf{A}| + |\\mathbf{B}|\\cos\\theta}\\right)\n\\]\n\n---\n\n### 3. Key Idea:\nThe triangular law of vectors is a consequence of the fact that vector addition is **commutative** and **associative**. The order in which vectors are added does not affect the resultant, and the vector addition can be visualized using the triangular arrangement.\n\n---\n\n### Final Notes:\nThe triangular law of vectors is a geometric interpretation of vector addition and is widely used in physics and engineering to analyze forces, displacements, and other vector quantities. It is closely related to the **Parallelogram Law of Vectors**, which is another way to represent vector addition.",
